{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":50611,"duration_api_ms":50511,"num_turns":7,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"c3bcdaaa-c86e-4d2c-894d-74d83c4f7752","total_cost_usd":0.28361424999999996,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":21988,"cache_read_input_tokens":136428,"output_tokens":1166,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":21988,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":6,"outputTokens":1166,"cacheReadInputTokens":136428,"cacheCreationInputTokens":21988,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.234819,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":31,"outputTokens":1755,"cacheReadInputTokens":75830,"cacheCreationInputTokens":25925,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.04879525,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Verified the amendment against the actual code. The cascading failure scenario is real and well-articulated. At line 5133, `run_snapshot_write.write_run_snapshot(...)` uses `?`, so if the snapshot write fails, the function returns early, skipping the run_failed journal event at lines 5136-5140. The irony is stark: the comments at lines 4643-4656 explicitly document the danger of journal/snapshot divergence and implement careful recovery via fail_run_result — but fail_run itself has the same vulnerability class. The journal event emission at 5138-5139 already uses best-effort semantics (`if let Ok` + `let _ =`), establishing that the developers intended it to be non-fatal. Applying the same best-effort pattern to the snapshot write at 5133 would be a low-risk, high-value improvement that ensures the journal event is at least attempted even under persistent disk I/O failure.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-19-e7673fe5","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed by reading the code. Line 5133 uses `?` on the snapshot write, causing early return on failure and skipping the run_failed journal event (lines 5136-5140). This is a genuine consistency defect in the error recovery path — the very path designed to prevent journal/snapshot divergence (as documented in the comments at lines 4643-4656) itself has the same class of bug. The fix is straightforward: replace the `?` at line 5133 with best-effort error handling (log the failure, continue to emit the journal event), matching the pattern already used at lines 5138-5139 for the journal append. Under persistent disk I/O failure, both writes will fail, but attempting the journal event is strictly better than bailing out. At minimum, a comment documenting this known double-failure limitation would prevent future developers from assuming the recovery path is fully robust."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"afea2574-e8e5-497d-b04c-268087cd29bf"}
